What is #define V 6?
This is a macro definition. 
It tells the compiler to replace every occurrence of the letter V with the number 6 throughout your code before it starts compiling.
-------------------------------------
call by value & call by reference

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
void fcall(int x){
    x=10000;
}
void fref(int &x){
    x=20000;
}
int main() {
    // cout<<"Hello World!";
    int n = 10;
    fcall(n); // copy
    cout<<n<<endl;
    fref(n);  //orignial ko change
    cout<<n;
    return 0;
}

Output
10
20000

Function Declarations vs. Definitions
C++ reads from top to bottom. If you call a function before you define it, the compiler will panic. You have two choices:

Define it above main(): Put the whole function at the top.

Declare it (Prototype): Tell the compiler "This function exists, I'll define it later."
// Declaration (Prototype)
void sayHello(); 

int main() {
    sayHello(); // Call
    return 0;
}

// Definition
void sayHello() {
    cout << "Hello!";
}
--------------------------
SCOPE in C++
definition - whole function - var is actual variable 
declaration  - only prototype - var is just a placeholder

-----------------------------
POINTERS

&  address of 
* 2 usages ar Pointer Declaration , De-reference

int a = 10;
cout<<a;
cout<<&a;

int a=10;
int *ptr=&a;       // declaration
cout<<ptr;
cout<<*ptr;       // de-reference

Pass by pointer - exact same as pass by reference , only thing is NULLPTR can be pass
passByPointer(int *ptr)
{
if(ptr!=NULLPTR)
{
 *ptr = 100;
}
int main()
{
 int num = 5;
 passByPointer(num);
 cout<<num;
}
